## âš™ï¸ Step-by-Step Guide

### **1ï¸âƒ£ Create Resource Group**
```bash
az group create --name myResourceGroup --location eastus
````

### **2ï¸âƒ£ Generate SSH Key (if not already created)**

```bash
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -f ~/.ssh/azure_vm_key -N ""
```

### **3ï¸âƒ£ Create Virtual Machine (CLI)**

```bash
az vm create \
  --resource-group myResourceGroup \
  --name myVM \
  --image UbuntuLTS \
  --admin-username azureuser \
  --ssh-key-values ~/.ssh/azure_vm_key.pub \
  --size Standard_B1s \
  --location eastus
```

### **4ï¸âƒ£ Open Port for SSH**

```bash
az vm open-port --resource-group myResourceGroup --name myVM --port 22
```

### **5ï¸âƒ£ Connect to the VM**

```bash
ssh -i ~/.ssh/azure_vm_key azureuser@<your_public_ip>
```

âœ… Youâ€™re now inside your Azure VM!

---

## ğŸ’¾ Attach and Mount a Data Disk

### **Create and Attach Disk**

```bash
az disk create --resource-group myResourceGroup --name myDataDisk --size-gb 10
az vm disk attach --resource-group myResourceGroup --vm-name myVM --name myDataDisk
```

### **Format & Mount Inside VM**

```bash
lsblk
sudo parted /dev/sdc --script mklabel gpt mkpart primary ext4 0% 100%
sudo mkfs.ext4 /dev/sdc1
sudo mkdir /data
sudo mount /dev/sdc1 /data
```

### **Persist Mount (Optional)**

```bash
UUID=$(sudo blkid -s UUID -o value /dev/sdc1)
echo "UUID=$UUID /data ext4 defaults,nofail 0 2" | sudo tee -a /etc/fstab
```

---

## ğŸ“ˆ Scaling the VM

### **Vertical Scaling (Resize VM)**

```bash
az vm deallocate --resource-group myResourceGroup --name myVM
az vm resize --resource-group myResourceGroup --name myVM --size Standard_B2s
az vm start --resource-group myResourceGroup --name myVM
```

### **Horizontal Scaling (VM Scale Set)**

```bash
az vmss create \
  --resource-group myResourceGroup \
  --name myScaleSet \
  --image UbuntuLTS \
  --admin-username azureuser \
  --ssh-key-values ~/.ssh/azure_vm_key.pub \
  --instance-count 2 \
  --upgrade-policy-mode automatic
```

---

## ğŸ” Useful Commands

```bash
# List VM Public IP
az vm list-ip-addresses -g myResourceGroup -n myVM --output table

# Check VM Status
az vm get-instance-view -g myResourceGroup -n myVM --output table

# List Scale Set Instances
az vmss list-instances -g myResourceGroup -n myScaleSet --output table
```

